<HEADLINE>
<P>
HINTS FROM HELOISE: MAKING AN INSTANT LID FROM HOT PLASTIC WRAP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: Last week I took some pork and beans in a glass bowl to a potluck 
dinner. I didn't have a lid for the bowl and I knew the beans would, no doubt, 
spill in my car on the way. 
</P>
<P>
Then I remembered how plastic wrap clings to the sides of any glass bowl when 
heated in the microwave oven. I heated the beans on HIGH (100%) for a couple of 
minutes and the plastic wrap created a tight seal so the beans didn't make a 
mess. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the lids on my casserole dishes aren't very tight, so this tip could 
also be used to make sure food doesn't spill while being transported even when 
it has a lid. Also, the plastic wrap seal keeps the food hot longer. 
</P>
<P>
 -- KELLY, Chandler, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR KEITH: There is an easy solution to this. Just mix one cup of rubbing 
alcohol to a quart of water and use this solution on the cloth when cleaning 
the freezer. Since rubbing alcohol will not freeze, the cloth will not stick. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: My mother-in-law told me the best way to make poached eggs. First 
of all, spray the pan lightly with a non-stick vegetable spray, fry the eggs 
until the whites are barely set, then add about one tablespoon of water. Cover 
tightly and turn the heat down very low. 
</P>
<P>
The result is a semi-poached egg that is not greasy and there is no turning 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
 -- RUTH, Honeoye, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
 Send a time- or money-saving hint to Heloise, P.O. Box 795000, San Antonio, 
Tex. 78279. Letters will not be answered personally, but the best hints 
received will be used in the Hints From Heloise column. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
