<HEADLINE>
<P>
COOK IT LIGHT: LESS IS MORE FOR TASTIER TREATS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNE JONES, Jones is a food consultant and a cookbook author. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR JEANNE: Please determine whether this recipe can be adjusted to lower the 
fat and cholesterol levels. It's delicious but dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
 -- VIRGINIA, Kenmore, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
SPINACH SQUARES 
</P>
<P>
1 cup flour 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon baking powder 
</P>
<P>
1 cup milk 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup margarine, melted 
</P>
<P>
2 eggs, beaten 
</P>
<P>
1 cup minced onion 
</P>
<P>
10 ounces Cheddar cheese, shredded 
</P>
<P>
10 ounces cooked spinach, drained thoroughly 
</P>
<P>
Combine flour, salt, baking powder, milk, margarine, eggs, onion, Cheddar 
cheese and spinach. Place in greased 9-inch square pan. Bake at 350 degrees 30 
minutes. Cut into squares. Makes 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
Note: May be baked 1 day ahead and reheated. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR VIRGINIA: This is a perfect example of when less is more. By simply 
reducing the problem ingredients in the recipe, you end up with a finished 
product that is more enjoyable from both a health and taste standpoint. 
</P>
<P>
The margarine was easily reduced by half and egg substitute worked beautifully 
in place of the eggs, so the fat and cholesterol are greatly reduced. I have 
found that low-fat Cheddar cheese is always appropriate as a substitute for the 
traditional high-fat variety, and I was able to reduce the amount of cheese 
called for without missing it. 
</P>
<P>
I think you will agree that this recipe gives more of everything you want from 
food by using less of the things you don't really need. 
</P>
<P>
 -- JEANNE 
</P>
<P>
REVISED SPINACH SQUARES 
</P>
<P>
1 cup unbleached flour 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon baking powder 
</P>
<P>
1 cup nonfat milk 
</P>
<P>
2 tablespoons corn-oil margarine, melted 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup liquid egg substitute 
</P>
<P>
1 cup minced onion 
</P>
<P>
6 ounces 20 % fat-reduced Cheddar cheese, shredded 
</P>
<P>
1 (10-ounce) package frozen spinach, cooked and well drained or 3/4 pound fresh 
spinach, chopped, steamed 2 minutes and well drained 
</P>
<P>
Combine flour, salt, baking powder, milk, margarine, egg substitute, onion, 
Cheddar cheese and spinach. Place in 9-inch square pan sprayed with non-stick 
vegetable coating. Bake at 350 degrees 30 minutes. Cut into squares. Makes 8 
servings. 
</P>
<P>
Note: May be baked 1 day ahead and reheated. 
</P>
<P>
Each serving contains approximately: 
</P>
<P>
Original Recipe: 
</P>
<P>
Calories: 355 
</P>
<P>
Cholesterol: 110 mg 
</P>
<P>
Fat: 26 gm 
</P>
<P>
Sodium: 750 mg 
</P>
<P>
Revised Recipe: 
</P>
<P>
Calories: 199 
</P>
<P>
Cholesterol: 19 mg 
</P>
<P>
Fat: 9 gm 
</P>
<P>
Sodium: 380 mg 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recipe; Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011989-0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 7092 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 19, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
