<TEXT>
<P>
An ugly smudge is widening in the once clear, blue water of Lake Tahoe because 
of man-made pollution and acid rain, said a scientist who has studied the lake 
for 30 years. Charles Goldman, a limnologist -- one who examines the physical, 
chemical and biological properties of fresh water -- told the American Assn. 
for the Advancement of Science meeting in San Francisco that there is 
"irrefutable scientific evidence one of the world's cleanest, largest, 
loveliest lakes is deteriorating at a predictable rate." He said pollution has 
caused algae to grow 5.5% a year, resulting in an annual water transparency 
loss of 1 foot. The area's wildlife, economy and drinking water are also 
threatened, Goldman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
